Eploratory Visualization of Ford Go-Bike Dataset¶

By: Ernest Edim¶

Introduction¶

Ford Go-Bike data from 2019 covers details of individual rides made in the bike-sharing system comprised by mostly the San Francisco Bay area. Many other cities are covered by the complete dataset. There are data for previous years as well, but I will be working on San Francisco. The data comprises 16 columns namely: duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The Ford Go-Bike dataset comprises 183412 rows (observations) and 16 columns focusing on the bike trip details; the trip duration, start and end times, start and end stations info, and some informations related to the users. Most columns are integers/floats with just 7 string data type.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The Trip duration might be the main feature of interest of this dataset, as it's for sure affect the revenue of the company, that's why I will study on this analysis the effect of other factors like user_type, trip start and end times, gender and age on the trip duration.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think the following features will support my investigation:

  • Trip duration
  • User type
  • Gender
  • Member ages
  • Start time (hour)
  • Start time (day of the week)

# histogram plot of duration_min to understand the distribution of the values
def trip_duration_min():
    #define a function to plot duration_min on a histogram to understand the distribution
    bin_size = 5
    bins = np.arange(0, data['ride_period_min'].max()+bin_size, bin_size)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=[9, 5])
    plt.hist(data = data, x = 'ride_period_min', bins = bins)
    plt.title('Histogram Plot of Trip Duration')
    plt.xlabel('Ride Period(min)')
    plt.ylabel('No. of Trips')
    plt.axis([-10, 200, 0, 80000])
In [455]:

In [458]:
def log_hist():
    # define a function to plot a log scale for our visualization
    bin_size_log = 0.025
    bins = 10 ** np.arange(0, np.log10(data['ride_period_min'].max())+bin_size_log, bin_size_log)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=[10, 5]);
    plt.hist(data = data, x = 'ride_period_min', bins = bins);
    plt.xscale('log');
    plt.xticks([1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100, 200, 500, 1000, 2000], [1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100, 200, 500, 1000, 2000]);
    plt.xlabel('Ride Period(min)');
    plt.ylabel('No. of Trips');

def trimmed_histplot():
    #function to plot a histogram on the trimmed duration
    bin_size_log = 0.02
    bins = 10 ** np.arange(0, np.log10(data['ride_period_min'].max()) + bin_size_log, bin_size_log)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=[9, 5]);
    plt.hist(data = data, x = 'ride_period_min', bins = bins);
    plt.xscale('log');
    plt.xticks([1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100, 200, 500, 1000, 2000], [1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100, 200, 500, 1000, 2000]);
    plt.title('Histogram Plot of Trip Duration (Minutes)')
    plt.xlabel('Ride Period.')
    plt.ylabel('No. of Rides')
    plt.show()

#create a plot for counts of start_time_dayofweek
def Ride_counts_Per_Weekday():
    #define a function to plot counts of dayofweek
    ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))
    sns.countplot(y = 'day', data = data, color = 'c')
    plt.title('Rides across days of the Week', fontweight = 'bold', fontsize = 13)
    plt.xlabel('No. of Rides')
    plt.ylabel('Day of the Week')

def plot_of_member_ages():

    plt.ylabel('No. of Riders')
    plt.show()

# CHecking the relationship between age of members and how much time their trips took
def ageVS_rideTime():
    # Define a function to plot duration and age
    plt.figure(figsize=[8,5])
    sns.scatterplot(data = data, x = 'age', y = 'ride_period_min', alpha = 0.25, marker = '.')
    plt.axis([10, 100, 1, 130])
    plt.title('Trip Duration and Age')
    plt.xlabel('Member Age')
    plt.ylabel('Ride Period (mins)')
    plt.show()
    print('The plot shows that riders between the ages of 20 and 40 years rode for longer time-upto 40 minutes while ages above 50 were only able to ride for shorter time. In essence, as the age of riders increased, the time spent riding reduced')

# Scatter plot of log transformed duration and member ages
def ageVSlogDuration():
    plt.figure(figsize=[20, 8])
    sns.scatterplot(data = data, x = 'age', y = 'ride_period_min', alpha = 0.5, s = 20, color = 'black')
    plt.title('Trip duration(log) and Member Age', fontsize = 14, fontweight = 'semibold')
    plt.xlabel('Member Ages');
    plt.yscale('log');
    plt.yticks([1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100], [1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100]);
    plt.ylabel('Ride period(mins.)');

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

  • My exploration of the number of rides each category of user took per every start hour showed that: a. Subscribers took the highest number of rides, b. Subscribers and customers started most trips during 8:00 hours and 17:00 hours, c. The least number of rides started at 3:00 and 4:00 hours.
